{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626482"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:39:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:39:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17079"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17079"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.73,0.08,0.1,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9769"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78000"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9769"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17079"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63422"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5259"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22947"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23170"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78000"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with a dental abscess. She reports being allergic to penicillin. The dentist prescribes clindamycin, a lincosamide antibiotic.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of lincosamide antibiotics?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits bacterial DNA gyrase","Binds to 50S ribosomal subunit to inhibit protein synthesis","Interferes with bacterial cell membrane integrity","Disrupts bacterial cell wall synthesis","Blocks bacterial folic acid synthesis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELincosamide antibiotics, including clindamycin, work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding to the 50S ribosomal subunit to inhibit protein synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E. This prevents the formation of peptide bonds during protein synthesis, resulting in bacteriostatic activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits bacterial DNA gyrase\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of fluoroquinolone antibiotics, which interfere with bacterial DNA replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterferes with bacterial cell membrane integrity\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of polymyxins and daptomycin, which disrupt the bacterial cell membrane structure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisrupts bacterial cell wall synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E describes a mechanism utilised by beta-lactam antibiotics such as penicillins, which prevent proper cell wall formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks bacterial folic acid synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of sulfonamides and trimethoprim, which interfere with bacterial folate metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELincosamides are particularly effective against anaerobic bacteria and are often used to treat infections caused by \u003Cem\u003EBacteroides fragilis\u003C/em\u003E and other anaerobes. They can also be used for infections caused by susceptible strains of \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E species.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lincosamide antibiotics work by binding to the 50S ribosomal subunit to inhibit bacterial protein synthesis.","Clindamycin is a commonly used lincosamide, with clinical utility in treating certain anaerobic and gram positive infections.","Lincosamides are bacteriostatic antibiotics that prevent bacterial growth rather than directly killing bacteria."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63422"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17079"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63422"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T22:02:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T22:02:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9769"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78000"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"m